column1: #Text=US Senate says no to pullout of US troops from Iraq

#Text=After a rare all-night session , the United States Senate voted today at 11 a.m. EST on the motion to invoke cloture of the Levin/Reed Amendment ( S. Amdt . 2087 ) which would begin a pullout of United States troops from Iraq , but only 52 votes were cast in favor of the amendment and 47 were cast against it , falling short of the 60 votes needed to overcome the Republican filibuster of the measure .
#Text=Cots were brought in for the Senators to catch snatches of sleep during the long night , while some slept at their Washington , D.C. apartments for short periods of time .
#Text=Pizza was brought in for senators to eat .
#Text=Seven Democrats left the Senate floor to join a candlelight vigil held outside across the street from Congress .
#Text=Had the bill passed , troops would have left Iraq 120 days after the vote , and would have been out of the country by April of 2008 .
#Text=Four Republican critics of the war — both of Maine 's senators , Susan Collins and Olympia Snowe , together with Chuck Hagel of Nebraska and Gordon Smith of Oregon — voted for the proposal .
#Text=Collins ' was a surprise vote ; although a critic , she has not been favorable toward the deadline approach .

#Text=Joe Lieberman , the Independent Democrat senator from Connecticut , who caucuses with Democrats , voted with Republicans against the motion , as he has done with all Iraq war legislation this year .
#Text=Last night during the all-night senate debate , Democratic Majority Leader from Nevada , Harry Reid , asked that the Senate vote on the bill this morning .
#Text=He later voted no on the motion in order to take advantage of Senate rules to reintroduce the measure .
#Text=After the motion failed , Reid proposed that the Senate look at a series of Iraq proposals , including the failed plan , and make them subject to a simple majority vote .
#Text=Mitch McConnell , the Republican Minority Leader from Kentucky objected , and Reid withdrew the legislation from the floor .
#Text=The Senate then moved on to discussing student loans and grants .

#Text=Throughout the night , the Senators took turns speaking in front of a large sign printed " Let Us Vote " , speaking in favor of the amendment and against the Republicans for not allowing a simple majority vote .
#Text=Republicans took turns decrying it , noting that Democrats did the same when they were the minority , and criticizing Democratic leaders .
